A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama’s Reelection
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, affirming that election fraud in the U.S. is less common than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of U.S. governments have passed new laws since 2009 that complicate the procedure for registration or voting.
This phenomenon gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana’s law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states forcing voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such a badge.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions affect young people, minorities and low-income people disproportionately.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are regarded as voters who vote more for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
It is clear that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators in eight states promoted laws abolishing voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters registered by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state's voters.
The same goes for the Hispanic population.
The latter made up only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, made up only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing the results in the decisive states for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral Board to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
