Analyzing the Higgs boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson last summer has aroused some stir, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but data is still lacking to be completely sure about.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, since there seems to be little risk of being deceived, and let’s take a look at what it’s all about.
There is an inevitably inevitable law in this world that makes it impossible for two objects to be present at the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to violate this rule – and don’t try too hard as you’ll be hurting yourself.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that it is also governed by one such law: the Paulian principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", and that "state" consists largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil gang of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred – certainly not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
However, it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electrical charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this location, somewhat like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be quarried by a very large rock.
This is why a huge particle accelerator such as CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon by the way) have no mass.
What can all this research be "good for," asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely study any deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (ups again!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-bar laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially seen as more of a "laboratory play."
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its committee on "Dignity Death", Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important topic.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him a two-year deadline.
"They gave me five years to live, I've made seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the home of palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he resigns to getting help with eating.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring his medications to him, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest wish is that you cure my diarrhea because it is humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing while standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
Because, according to several people working in palliative care, large events take place in the midst of these regressions.
Patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who take care of them.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by suffocation.”
But through the disease, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
“I don’t have any desires in life anymore,” she says before accepting that you put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offers personal care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, a bed for palliative care is available for 11,700 people.
This is very little, considering that we will all die someday.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," says Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, there is no day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family gathering in the yard and is well supported by his pillows as one pushes in his honor, a 36-year-old man surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children tragically dies after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients aged less than 45 years," Dr. Christiane Martel said in a statement.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stages of their lives, either at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Home Palliative Care Society in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this major inadequacy in Quebec’s healthcare that causes several palliative care specialists to face the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before accepting to move to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking any measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients will only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients with bitterness until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
The chances of Hélène Richard’s survival were already minimal when she discontinued a laborious chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not giving in to this desire after their pain has been alleviated by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Society of Home Palliative Care, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which amounts to either sporadically or permanently putting the patient to sleep until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
The realization of this report was possible due to a journalism scholarship from Canadian health research institutes.
