The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aid: girls and boys high schools, Institute of French at universities, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support of the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a "civil-military actions" service of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), discontinued in 2012, has carried out numerous non-profit work and measures for the rehabilitation of agriculture in dozens of mountain villages and has been carried out by a small French non-governmental organization in order to try to "gain the hearts and spirits" and achieve the impossible task of reconciling aid and offensive actions.
This work, which required a large number of local workers, has helped to suppress the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase in agricultural land.
What souvenir do we leave behind after military spending of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will help improve local living conditions, which are very tough in these valleys, often at an altitude of more than 2000 meters.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural projects from municipalities in the province of Kapisa.
In order for farmers to free themselves from the insurrection led by foreign groups, which they say is their wish, it would be necessary to continue with less, more well-controlled and directly relevant civilian aid in their favour.
A Constitution with a Brechstange in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, it has decided to put everything on one card.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a preliminary, amended text for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only contributed to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “tread the law with his feet.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
According to affirmations in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited authority", the latter supposedly should come to an end after the Constitution is adopted.
85 largely Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned their backs on their belief that they were unable to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly was not exactly going.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, is ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made more stringent application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda attack, reply “hypocrisy.”
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to checking compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, as "the persons who are asked to make a statement have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
You can see here the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system," Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition, said in a statement.
He admits, however, that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide about it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of controversy: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the audit of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Likewise, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as demanded by the associations for the defence of human rights.
The latter also share their concerns about the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
Blasphemy is being maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch stresses that no longer an article refers to the protection of women.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons to visit Israel.
Bowing down before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, calming the sea storm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries can be found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers take the Passion Way or Cross Way of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the site of the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a journey to the heights
The ruins of Massada fortress form the remains of the secret hiding from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rocky wall in the mountains at an altitude of 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
All others bring a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visit Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited with just one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathing servants of the time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells about one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the Children’s Memorial, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the lands in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
Israel’s three main recreational areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and it is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salinity and, as a result, even non-swimmers carry on the surface without any problems.
The surrounding countryside is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt salt) and healing mud, as well as for the treatment of inflammations of the skin, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to soothe stressed nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets lie in the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, passed through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
Fortune, according to legend, is held by all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newly married couples from all over Israel and even from other countries at photo meetings.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the Crusader Fortress.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre nowadays hosts evening concerts and operas.
Watchlist for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is preferred not in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged for shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city, you can usually travel by bus, but there is also a highway in Jerusalem and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport stops.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and food that contains both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from a variety of dishes of ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
There are many well-fed cats that stray through the streets comfortably and unhindered.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the rooftops of parked cars.
Cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Entrance tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the US and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families that remain in the home.
On December 1st, a law came into force that requires every working migrant to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, the municipal housing industry and the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
You have to pass not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language proficiency must be demonstrated both for obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas prior to the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The entirety of the examination bodies will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Nations, the Moscow State University, the Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, repeatedly asked the following question in the press before the law came into force: What does it all mean?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, according to spokespersons of the migration authority, the aim is to reduce the number of forced laborers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelev.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical expertise encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure with dozens of months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland, you will be promised one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, their passports will be taken off and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Central Office for Labour Migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not know the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: Only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately take the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of the migrant workers continue to stay illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Unauthorized access forbidden"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The Russian police staff know that our documents are largely forged and we are not registered, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Just don't shy away from costs for wrong papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the migrant’s registration documents could be counterfeit.
Some fake certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a working migrant three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Ministry of the Interior ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences is extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior plans to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
The authorities are responding to recent events: injuries in shootings at weddings and seven deaths in the shooting of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and increase the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chair of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "drawing the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - are demanding that the authorities refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, says former Colonel Viktor Baránez, who spent ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapon orders
The first channel is the army, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
On the second channel, illegal weapons are being stolen by law enforcement officers.
Baránez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police’s armory and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons stores.
In many military camps there were frequent explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the absence of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armaments factories that do not withstand international competition and that is why they squander weapons on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to the investigators, come from the army and the legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market are due to the "guilt of those responsible who have been involved in their work with weapons," according to the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% are due to thefts in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant to an arms store, who does not want to be named, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have not been bought by anyone for a long time, as they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for merchants to obtain supplies in a weapons store.
A gun, for example, a TT-type pistol, is purchased through an ensign.
The weapon is placed and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros each with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and, therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to detect crime, periodically carry out check purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
Buyers and sellers find each other most often through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone caught my attention and suggested that I come to the station "Begovaja", where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
The price of the gun was only there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are merchants in the markets, but there you have to go and meet with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who tells you that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I’m even getting to some hit rings about a friend I trust.
