- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and concise gestures rather than expansive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How's that?
- For example, would you ask me to pass you this bubble can?
They say it and point it out at the same time.
- Normally I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does this mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it's about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future, we will have to work primarily on developing new sensor types that will allow us to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they provide a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What are your requirements for modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
In this way, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and Y-axis, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and the number of images per second are also important.
Man's movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are too little, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond lab with an adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
