- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What are the answers your group wants to give to this objection?
In my lectures, I often speak of expanded reality as the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She perceives pressure excellently!
However, there are also technologies that are actually oriented to give the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is currently still as weak as if someone was blowing over the palms.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Did you try to outsmart the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he should feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed room believe that he is instead in an open, virtually infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), movable platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outwitted, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is exactly what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
