Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer steroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board set off in search of a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises, how can we reproduce in weightlessness or on the substitute planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Notably Mars and Venus," says the scientist at the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, a temperature of 500 degrees prevails on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The question of reproduction in space was first dealt with with regard to the flora.
Half a century before that, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of orbitally grown peas did not differ in any way from the earthly species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects embryo development.
It develops a very normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a hold; it has to be able to stand on its legs and start to move," explains the laboratory leader of the Institute of Medical Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid surface, the chicks overwhelmed themselves wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborn completely blunted.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks hatch and then set the whole thing up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," notes Vladimir Sychev on the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized sent into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to continue," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats had offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals ripped out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive instincts.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was in Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Will she survive the spaceflight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"After all, no one answered that question," says space veteran Wattang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaya, who was twice in orbit and even performed work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts who did well after long flights and had healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is, even on flights in orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valery Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet, humanity must look for new paths in biotechnology, radiation protection and the production of artificial gravity.
The hydro lab in the preparation center of the cosmonauts is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here, in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even though adults find water pleasant, it is a strange environment; however, infants feel water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders were testifying that life on the land escaped the ocean.
There is a correlation between the fact that a child is in the mother's belly in amniotic fluid for about 9 months, and that it can then more easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks pass from birth to the first swim.
"This is not enough time to forget something," says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenowa.
So, while for a newborn child, weightlessness is a much more natural state, the woman does not live without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles recover enormously quickly and thus the ability to squeeze the child out also decreases.
All right, let's get around this with birth-initiating aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valery Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the attraction of the earth, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in a stress suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply miss what is essential to his life.
"This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will result in us giving birth to a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person," says Igor Pestov, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical Biological Problems at the RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
Eventually, however, it will become a reality when the Earth’s inhabitants set out in their spaceships to a distant planet that will become the home for their offspring born in space.
