So far, we are more likely to experience effects in the preparatory phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognition of risks of ineconomicity" and examined and analyzed almost 14,000 public contracts - here the changes will of course have an impact as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you think the adoption of this law is more positive, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, there may be the problem that the rules become "strenger" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to audit are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) in such a way that any non-compliance with the public procurement law constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a formal flaw that does not affect the actual decision making.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out here?
First, let’s say which path is not appropriate.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not trouble entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system forbidden or allowed?
A law must be valid, and if something is forbidden by law, then it cannot simply come to the chairman of the government, and the control office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, hinder its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say we're pretending nothing.
The Public Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, however, it is also tragic when the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be properly applied - and that is what I think is missing from us.
