Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked so far without problems, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I sometimes wondered sometimes already.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travels abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than we do, we have just witnessed in Russia that in the East everything is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible to people with disabilities. There, it is still unusual for someone in a wheelchair to travel alone in the city center.
It is not even self-evident there that a wheelchair user is left in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things we hang out in afterwards...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to also be able to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common that a larger group of disabled people actively participate in social events there, in this we are with the band The Tap Tap a little ahead of the West!
Public respect and accessibility is one thing, but only when major athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensively.
