It is interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalized world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause of this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of work (wages), price tensions arise.
This term refers to a situation in which the manufacturer attempts to compete economically by importing favourable goods by "undercutting" competition in order to gain a larger market share and increase profits.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to relocate their production abroad or buy cheaply there, or to quit their business, resulting in high unemployment in countries with comparablely high labour costs.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is further aggravated by the fact that the entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage they cause to society as a whole.
This situation is well known, so that concrete statistics are unnecessary at this point.
The reckless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own people to private capital regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done on the one hand by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand by the restriction of workers' rights.
The result is increasing poverty, as well as increasing differences between rich and poor.
In Germany, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for several years, who are no longer able to feed themselves by their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which employees receive such a low wage that the state has to increase their income to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also revealed in the case of auxiliary workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures taken by virtually all EU southern states will undoubtedly result in the same condition where people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) under the pressure of a catastrophic crash of their social level, or to live on the edge of society for a starvation wage, hoping that private investment capital will eventually flow into the country.
This naturally raises the question of where this capital comes from.
If it comes from another EU country, poverty simply moves from one country to another; or the capital stays completely out, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa at all, the workers work for a fraction of the European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim to the exasperation that the state is not allowed to participate in its own national economy with capital, and that a planned economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists narrowly on its view that the state must not intervene steeringly in the economy.
Then one has to wonder, however, whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the entire state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually almighty lobby that is omnipresent in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, mutual preference, a legislation in which practically everything is punishable but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is that, due to a lack of finances, a state ministry commissions private legal firms closely intertwined with the industry with the preparation of draft laws.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer comes from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Apparently, the liberal democracies are currently quickly in a situation as described by Appian in his work on the crisis of the Roman republic in the times of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in disintegration, and the offices were occupied by force.
Against bribes, through unlawful concealment of advantages, or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew rampant, and the people went to the election with votes already bought" ... "People with character did not apply for office, so that the state had not had a consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "It was already really started to talk about that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a sovereignty, and that a strong man then had to be elected by the C...
As it turns out, today’s society, as in ancient times, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital is by its very nature incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for the whole society.
The result, today as then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not at all striving for deeper reforms.
The cause of the rise of fascism and communism must therefore be sought in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today's standpoint, the downfall of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause, during which the next round is already looming.
Especially disastrous is the fact that today’s elites face the possible losses of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from older and more recent history, in complete ignorance.
The repeal of the law on non-profit work is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for ways to push the social level of the population down.
