The movie Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt at hostage liberation only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages evoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy officials managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, while an extravagant story helped them conceal their true identity – travelling with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff that allegedly visited the country's filming locations for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
In order to make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret, and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful piece of Hussars such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film alternate - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly overshadowed.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the office hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable relaunch of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime novel No Kindle (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not set in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that set the previous films of this director apart from the standard of Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this sense in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the opening sequence of the assault on the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film rod on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the little he works quite successfully, but sometimes he helps with reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserved more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of traction, and it’s a film that you can follow with a certain interest, while gouting the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is difficult to awaken enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is alive to this day in a certain way and as a proof of how overwhelming the notions of the almighty and omniscient intelligence services are.
