The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a nearby large-scale company, says: "But it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of these old-style libraries voluntarily today, right?
Spijkenisse, a hardly visitable sleeping city on the outskirts of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-population community has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to the general education and to recreate the seven fictional bridges depicted on the euro notes as beautifully brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of the bold bar diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with usual serenity and appeared for the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury looked around, stunned, and shrugging their arms, the cheeky Maas piled his exquisite souvenirs of greatness into a pyramid and ended his actionist-supported speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So that is it, my proposal for the Buchberg von Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain is spilled.
It is part of a revitalization project that includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjoining residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Buchenberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is the faceless small town restaurant, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian street and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: Book Torado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true pleasures of space and reading open up as you climb the topography on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights unmistakably speak the language of a public square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, the bookshelves are located along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and pushed the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the center are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center.
A special joy are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes parapets, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even industrious architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so one day we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years, in the Netherlands, a millimetre-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root pad in greenhouses and fields.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts for one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - to plates four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells like a new car and a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 meters long hike, the Literaturcafé not only offers a fantastic view of the city, but also rewards you with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all for the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bücherberg stands under a glass fall, the sun shines only briefly in the interior, even on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand across the glass facade, serve as shadows and capture a large part of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already dared to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg Spijkenisses "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal inventory.
For the time being, this is intended to fill the optical gaps in the not yet fully stocked library - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has opened up.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV has succeeded in the royal discipline that is called the Identity Foundation in the technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing at a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
Then Berlin abstained.
- Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany has to be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
To make matters worse, Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching on their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like they have France or Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy actually mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, into the head in the Arab countries.
That definitely plays a role.
But I wouldn't put too much weight on it either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the US.
Therefore, I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Maybe Germany will even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that as an international player, it must be taken seriously and its interests must be taken into consideration.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there disagreements between the United States and many European nations?
Due to American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think that the Obama administration secretly has quite a bit of understanding for the European position.
But due to the political situation here, of course, the government cannot publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual disagreements are not as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other hand?
I think that’s what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can’t be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
This is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future, Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
