Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human Pappilomaviruses, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Felt aphids and scabies are among the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and trippers occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), tripper and human pappilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - nevertheless: About 20 percent of HIV new infections account for this group.
Chlamydia infections occur much more frequently among adolescents than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, Human Pappilomaviruses are also common among adolescents.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has declined since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of venereal disease?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, lower abdomen pain, as well as blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer 100% protection.
Because in part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricating infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
Diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and late consequences can be avoided.
