Tens of thousands gathered in unfamiliar harmony at Tahrir Square in Cairo on Friday evening, vowing to bring the Charter down before it can enter into force.
"The revolution has returned and we will win," said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-placed in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and ex-chief of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El-Baradei stated that the draft constitution belongs “to the rubbish pile of history.”
On Twitter, he accused Morsi of wanting to lead a “putch against democracy.”
"If he declares the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," said opposition leader Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali.
And several judges announced that they would not monitor the referendum, which would invalidate it.
“The Qur’an is our Constitution.”
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew up for counter-demonstration, but as a precaution, not on Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other bank of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
Many veiled women and supporters of the Salafists took part, shouting, "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded of Morsi, "Cleave the land!" and asserted, "The Qur'an is our constitution."
A battle for supremacy over the emblematic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would have probably evoked civil war-like conditions.
Obviously, Mursi's followers didn't want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood declared that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the proponents had expressed themselves loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority in favour of the Islamist draft is deemed to be secure.
"The word human rights doesn't even occur"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process, which should have gone through February and should involve all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he complained in an interview with the "Welt am Sonntag".
Morsi’s extension of power to all three powers in the state caused the lawyer to resign.
These measures are flagrant violations of democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto overturns it," Saeda said.
But without civil society organizations, democracy cannot work.
Saeda feels left alone, also by the international community, which looks at the ideological directional struggle on the Nile with a mix of curiosity and tension.
It could take revenge.
A demonstrator on the Tahrir warns, "You are giving birth to a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most nasty fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards – not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret to success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty bad-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the midst of a pile of dirty, moist sportswear.
Leave it there for a week.
One must imagine the anesthetizing smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt that ferments in water for up to a year, depending on how stinky you would like your fish to be.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this, well, really, very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk general".
People around us eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Many people like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirit can displace the smell.
I'm going to try some appetizers.
If you avoid bringing the Rakfisk near your nose, it’s not bad – like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, far poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling options and fish was soaked in airtight salt water barrels in the autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then taken out after long fermentation and - undoubtedly using alcohol-damped senses - consumed.
Even a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians in search of work were forced to leave their country and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and comprehensive healthcare.
Even from Sweden, the old rival who was far richer than Norway not too long ago, immigrants flock.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important - an essential, albeit strictly smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t get into the world press often, and most people don’t seem to bother.
Anders Breivik is the racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the "July 22 incident".
Norwegians find it hard to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Mainly responsible for Norway’s current wealth since the early 1970s has been the growth of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with mature rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a cautious people.
Your English is immaculate, just like most people here.
We are not very assertive, we do not like bragging.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very cautiously – a large part of the industry’s income is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the Great Depression, everyone threw money around them that they did not own at all, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And, of course, eat rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and ask for another dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
A moose burger like that is definitely something else. The juicy meat makes me feel good.
But in the evening, the stink fish is on the menu again.
The hotel I’m staying at is one of several venues that organize a rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most challenging – fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jurgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard".
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the strict mist of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
As Mexico’s future president Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC’s Will Grant analyzes the challenges facing him and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this city is always clogged, but on Monday a steel ring was erected, which blocks several important traffic routes into the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new President Enrique Peña Nieto will receive the presidential tie and take the lead of the nation.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before reaching an equal position with the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute it to the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represent a major improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and ongoing changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Peña Nieto party, the PRI.
In particular, in terms of security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high expectations for Enrique Peña Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all, he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, dozens of murdered women have been left dead on a patch of wasteland near a large landfill.
During the reign of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics of Pena Nieto believe that he has at least not addressed the problem of women's killings during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government closed their eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the degraded neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with the tears as she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her life partner.
"When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the corpse rigidity had already been used.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down at us from the wall. It is attached to a cross that bears a single word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a talker, a troublemaker, a noisy.
They want you to simply accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible when there were so many formal flaws and omissions,” she says.
When President Peña Nieto receives the presidential leash on Saturday, he will also take on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes in the last six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this issue during his term in office.
"I hope as president he is as he was as governor," said Olvera, a member of the PRI Congress, in Valle del Bravo.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear the most.
The prosecution claims Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
The prosecution contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations that he was mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a dismissal of the indictment on the grounds of too harsh detention conditions
U.S. Army Soldier Accused of Stealing Thousands of Confidential Documents
The prosecution tried on Friday to establish that Army Freeman Bradley Manning — accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history — missed several occasions to complain about the alleged abuse he allegedly suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning’s nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the indictment - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard jail term - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been imprisoned from July 2010 to April 2011 under enhanced detention conditions.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein questioned him on the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had assessed the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, Fein said, contained no complaints about abuse, although officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns verbally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been logged.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) 'no problems', and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to downgrade his observation status to “prevent injury.”
The military testified that it had assigned it to this restrictive status – which is one level below the risk of suicide – for his own and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of the observational status for injury prevention (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and relocation to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to Quantico Marine Base Prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he was considering suicide in Kuwait and had been unconscious due to the heat.
Not being allowed to know what is happening to him or the outside world was burdensome.
"My world shrank on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
If he had turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, they would have woken him up so that he would turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's attorney formally appealed Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Military Prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, the judge also questioned Manning on an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
When interviewed on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night and had previously tried to show an official that he was not posing a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning testified, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take his detention experiences into account and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted at his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for the beginning of next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will confess to minor offenses, while other charges that are deemed too extreme will be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend. Prosecutors are expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all detainees detained under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
Manning’s charges include favoring the enemy, unlawful disclosure of intelligence information on the Internet, the transmission of national defense information, and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants - they evoke hard times in their minds, he says
Navarrete believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when perplexity spread within me.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure of where to go.
I grew up in Central California and have been called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians."
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have a native speaker’s vocabulary, and I don’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and lined up for extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico than to emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Peña Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war on the drug cartels, even though he did not give any details on this.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership to leave more than half of their territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, you hear – in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites – complaints about how the Americans are threatening the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma embark on the war path.
And yet, in reality, Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because at one point in our pedigree, a person — perhaps a parent or grandparent — was not offered a chance in Mexico and emigrated north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our allegiance is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may have now lived the American dream, attended good schools, and gotten good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we live – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that tensions exist between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican-Americans are taking this to heart.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know have the feeling of belonging neither to one country nor to another.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and sections of the educational bourgeoisie want to re-establish their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional “ambassadors” to Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well, now.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through that alone, amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge about how their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such a hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual blaming, countless buildings have been laid to rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time rockets from Gaza have been hit near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East around them is changing.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly standstill could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week’s fights have strengthened the hardened on both sides.
The leader of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though its group itself suffered major losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip have been enclosed in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders could conclude that they have the time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to attract powerful and wealthy friends to its side.
Turkey, a re-established regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken sides for Hamas – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheering Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah holds power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist nature could face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – by far the most populous and important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has sustainably changed the region’s balance.
Hosni Mubarak, the laicist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is tied to Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more calmly.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States is steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers – not least thanks to the barriers that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of any Palestinian state – protecting Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal but are continuing to expand.
Netanyahu’s Likud party allied itself with an even more combative group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these devious Palestinians also cheat and leave them with a state of their own?
If they actually had control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire missiles just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it is better to keep them behind the wall at bay and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could be a blow to them.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments repair their economy.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi joined forces with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign — and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think long-term.
As the rest of the Arab world takes timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder barrel that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside.
The correct answer is that represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, most of the rest of the world and this newspaper: two states where Israel surrenders territories for security purposes.
The hope – small for the near future – is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, along with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms supplies to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama must also play his part in persuading Israel to negotiate.
During his first term in office, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is equally reluctant to participate.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a significant interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian legislation on uniform cigarette packaging enters into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children affected by cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, will be on Saturday.
Australia is implementing the world’s most stringent regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
Studies have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at 26 are 99% more likely to stop smoking afterwards.
"You can see from a young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a slight impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favor the black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone covers to cover the intolerable packaging has risen tremendously since corporations British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws at the Supreme Australian Court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
This is a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media lies with exactly the population group that the plan is targeting.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from appearing as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop laying out cigarettes in stores.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising from local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Those who market tobacco and have only a small area left to promote their products won’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a researcher in health care at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has noticed an increase in brand experiences written by “very normal people.”
You have to ask yourself: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that she even records a video for it - or does a marketing agency have anything to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of focusing on marketing, the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay the Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of the countries engages in major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings in 2001.
In the meantime, these have been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a tilt and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box, on which a photo with a mouth tumor is printed.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd quit, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco trade "King of the Pack" in downtown Sydney, says the uniform packaging has made it difficult to fill up its shelves.
"I used to need an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four," Yu says.
"The government should have banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said to each other 'okay, that's it, we're closing down,'" he added.
In a constantly electrified world, it is nice to be bored sometimes
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane went down due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think about getting bored.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying - even when books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us — and our kids — to be bored occasionally.
In this way, the brain is forced to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us nowadays almost constantly stare at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah, yeah.
And no, no.
I will come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't see it that way.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
Pompeii’s house walls adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After long reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of “wanting to do a satisfactory job but not being able to do it”.
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
In apathy, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a “disturbance of the attention process coupled with bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly.”
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions might be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German for example: "The idle mind: The definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the hardly audible television said they felt more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could not find a reason for them, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, disturbing attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous activity - "such as searching for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not feel bored."
In fact, he says, we now know that babbling and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people physically more attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a roaring loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
Some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "scalar of long-term vulnerability".
On the scale, statements such as "A lot of things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to become boring than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – particularly when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty laid-back bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents in school and doing homework were bored, whereas 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is certain that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a major influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it leads people to take extreme physical risks and go to gambling or drugs to alleviate them – studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something different,” said Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do right now.
If you are bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you will be happy.
But television can cause feelings of happiness in the short term, but these disappear again in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, it can dissuade him from being bored, but he has not learned how to entertain himself or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, “Self-control transfers from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from the constant activity and technology spraying.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be boring more often, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth, people are only looking for a way to shut down and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to keep busy once the noise is silenced."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
19-year-old community college student and soccer player Anthony Orozco is on trial in southeastern Colorado for an offense that will soon be legal in that state: owning a few marijuana chunks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving a car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug utensils — cavalry offences, each with a $100 penalty — and was given a court date.
"We are being treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for its own use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug offences depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of lawsuits about marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
The police authorities will no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for possession to a small extent, which will be allowed by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative districts of Colorado have announced that they will continue to prosecute existing marijuana offenses and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the Denver suburbs to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
"This situation is evolving so quickly that I don't know what's going to happen next," said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on the establishment of a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline in mind for 1 December 2013.
In Washington, Colorado is believed to be ahead of most states when it comes to regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is a good place to guide," said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Spirits Supervisory Board.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
"We don't have a real precedent that we can follow," he adds.
The Washington Act, called I-502, enters into force on December 6 and thus also marks the end point of a gray zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time – for example, how the government’s requirement for “appropriate access” to licensed marijuana should be agreed with the ban on cannabis stores within 300 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the metropolitan area of Seattle,” said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his Aurora staff stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in individuals over the age of 21, and that the police would “as of now” not seek criminal charges for these offenses.
Chief Oates added that police will continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate growers of medical marijuana and drug traffickers will continue to be persecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck holds a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his agency would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mainly to persuade consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have to stand trial for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have also been indicted for other crimes.
“Our agency has a duty to prosecute violations that were criminal at the time of the crime,” Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are ambiguous even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, are no longer reporting adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending ownership proceedings.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile the personal use of marijuana with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the contradictory reactions throughout the state revealed a profound disagreement among local officials about the great green experiment.
District prosecutors are a "cultural barrier," says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents the defendant in court for marijuana crimes and acts as a spokesperson for the national organization to reform marijuana laws.
“They’ve spent such a large part of their lives prosecuting people for it that they still can’t accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being traded as national model cases for drug legalization.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an age of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue treating the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several striking arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officials are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of the drugs, they are likely to be reluctant to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local municipalities approved moratoriums for new marijuana stores, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban, which is likely to be passed next week.
"We don't want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level," said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community has voted against this change in the law.
We are determined by what the community has decided on, not by what the state has decided on.
There are still many questions to be asked.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only today’s university students are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my elder brother had attended that university which I once thought was the greatest knowledge stamp in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization—free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my entry into Worscester College in the late 1980s - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again and caused the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I had left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A.N. Wilson said that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason – one that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my now-deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was an advocate of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of moderate right-wing students are suffering similar persecution.
The organised and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has grown to such dimensions that a group of them demanded equal protection last week to benefit gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked, and declared undesirable" because of their political views.
They are demanding a seat on their college’s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was exacerbated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as an eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the University of Oxford Conservative Student Association, who rode a Rolls-Royce and wore a silver-coloured suit and a silver-painted walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered "sin-blocks for introducing higher tuition fees."
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the University of Nottingham Conservative Students' Association, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing left-wing tendency in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know us."
Samuel Roberts, 21, and a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the request for greater protection, believes that such a climate is “unpleasant,” and 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has witnessed a growing rejection of moderate right-wing students among JCR members.
"This poses a threat to the intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members," she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I had arrived in September 1986.
The hatred for the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to grant Margaret Thatcher – a former student – an honorary degree due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have terrified even Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students got to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what was going on.
I experienced that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated in it with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, the privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been prepared for what would come next.
“Miss Wyatt,” said Harry Pitt, “please translate the first paragraph.”
I stumbled upon it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite hateful.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students laughed.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest you take a few French lessons in your free time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt grumbled to me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting in college alone at dinner when someone gently tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who envisioned himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory will be harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory first-semester students claim to be Labour supporters.
In a local pub I later tried to disguise myself.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A graduate in philosophy, politics, and economics who ironically had attended Eton College, considered conservative, said to me, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're polluted.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" someone asked me.
They beat each other, don't they?
I felt the same way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever succeed in living a normal life at the University of Oxford?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me stretched before my spiritual eye into a purgatory of disgrace and isolation.
The only tutor who openly recognized himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also because he advised Thatcher on foreign policy and wrote speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for his Marxist-determinist history perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the forties, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said.
They would never do that, not in my city of dreaming tower tops.
Even my Communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His damp eyes darkened.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had succumbed to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly shattered by shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to a “brainwashing” and called them “old fools.”
The relief only lasted for a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my hammers gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You're welcome to call me a weeping cock.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to celebrity"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which opened in London this week, ABC speaks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion maker.
Somerset House, the former residence of Isabel I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
This was acknowledged by the designer at the opening of "Valentino - Master of Couture", a grandiose retrospective for which more than 130 Haute Couture dresses created by his "Maison" over the last 50 years have been compiled.
"I love this palace," he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition concludes a story whose sole protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the stuffy and distant world of nobility.
In the first hall of this exhibition, which will be on display until March 3rd, there are a variety of private letters and photos with the signature of the most exquisite aristocracy, starting with Princess Salimah Aga Khan, Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margarita of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise from the humble fashionmaker in the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of international jet set.
Being in love with the nobility does not have to be a disadvantage.
"At least they don't kick their ticks on your gorgeous carpet, as some beautiful celebrities from pop music do," says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, the two lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all happy when we were invited to his house in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, close friends with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to celebrity.
And yet he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, in a dress by Valentino
Also the Argentine model Valeria Mazza does not forget the charisma of the fashionmaker.
Many years ago, after a fashion show at Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went home to him for dinner.
We were about 20 people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
Every detail of his apartment, the decoration, the food and the music recognized and felt his influence.
"All the guests felt important and loved," recalls the "top model" that began her career at the 1995 Paris Haute Couture Week.
“He never goes out of fashion because his designs are works of art,” she concludes.
Fashion show of origin
The life of Garavani is not a story of obsession, rather of mutual loves.
He likes people with good education and the highest titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glorious and 60-meter-long catwalk that suggests a role exchange: the user takes the model's place and walks along the catwalk to admire a dreamlike "audience" wearing Valentino's masterpieces, such as the dress that belonged to Jackie Kennedy for her wedding with Aristóteles Onassis, who chose "the Emperor's"
In this audience of fashion dolls radiate names such as that of Sibilla de Luxemburgo, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sofía of Habsburg.
Naty Abascal and the Fashion Maker, 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino is like the first love, "unforgettable".
I can still remember perfectly.
It was a pants, a shirt, a vest type "Gillette" and a jacket from the autumn/winter collection 1971-1972.
“It was a gift from him,” says Naty Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
"I prefer him to everyone else because of his great love for women and because he highlights our beauty," Feria's ex-duchess added.
I like the colors he uses very much; they have a lot of light and underline the face.
The proportions are perfect.
Even the princess and fashion leader Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg cannot forget the first time she wore a Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamt of finally having the age and the opportunity to wear one of his evening dresses...
At the end of the 90s, it finally happened.
I bought my first Valentino dress for a party in the castle of my cousin, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red dress with a flying skirt and a draped top with a décolleté that honors his name.
"It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino doesn't depend on fashion, his obsession is timeless," explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess D'Arenberg keeps her evening dresses of the fashion maker "with absolute care, because a dress is not only a dress, but also the associated memories."
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is the wedding dress of Marie-Chantal Miller for her wedding with Pablo de Grecia in 1995.
Four months of work and 25 "ragazzes" (as the fashionmaker called his seamstresses) were necessary to make this ivory silk dress with beads, twelve different embroidery and a four and a half meters long tail.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the supreme authority of the trade press, this dress was a milestone in haute couture at the end of the 20th century, "the return to the customers of the supreme society."
For years clouded with the "savoir-être" of the elite, Valentino is now their best specimen.
Cavaliere di Gran Croce (the highest award in Italy), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres, awarded with the Legion of Honor, cumulates Garavani as many honors as any of the husbands of his clients.
"I have always noticed his refinement, his tranquility, his well-kept and perfect appearance," admits D'Arenberg.
I last saw him a month ago at a gala dinner at the Museum de Orsay.
He sat at the table of Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, a very good friend of mine.
"He was immaculate; time leaves no trace on him".
And this is what a princess says...
The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers risk their lives and health as they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, stony roads.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earned their lives by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in eastern Indonesia’s Java island.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfur-containing gas emerging from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths of stone.
While it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent at the turtle pace, keeping the balance and making their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they pave the way between the tourists, who photograph them like circus monkeys, and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the volcano and (never better said) its workers since 1960, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 cents), because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used to produce matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even bleaching sugar.
"Because we normally carry 70 kg, we receive about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally does three routes a day.
For each track it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn from the field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where at the coffee harvest 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees a day, and the work wasn’t that hard, but Anto and his family returned to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason as important as sulfur in Indonesia: “I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam.”
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at the Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left the first traces on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he promises in a more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a dragnet.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other wearers and gets up every morning at two o’clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
Approximately 400 carriers load the baskets with sulphur on their shoulders at the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera, which the guardians of this nature park charge, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
“This work is for animals and not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a strong, 42-year-old supporter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
