Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven present rulers.
Efe repeatedly attempted to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Initially, sources in the state and presidential office told them that they would hand it over after the exit, but later stated that it would be published on the Peruvian government’s website at some point.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the summit was restricted at any time.
During the day, only the picture of the presidential meeting without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulating among the journalists was obtained from the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document circulating during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the presidential office of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was the Humala statement and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit South America-Arab States (ASPA), and on this occasion too, despite the press' insistent request, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for the journalists were available, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of The Hague that resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICC, which will begin Monday in The Hague, in the process that Lima initiated against Santiago to listen to the pleadings of both sides.
"We will comply with and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently bringing to this international court," Humala said in a statement.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," added Piñera, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the ICC came after Colombia filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá Agreement after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, agreeing to submit to the judgments of this international court.
Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner, attended the summit.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after the deposing of its president, Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Hosting President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, stating that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of $17 billion.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said that Unasur countries will “take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the decisions on residence rights.”
He said action was being driven to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organized cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take triumphant steps, but serve to expand our production output and show our peoples a better future,” Humala added.
“We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects that will improve spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas...and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms,” the Peruvian president said in a read-only statement.
Among these projects are five Peruvians, located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also made reference to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its resumption into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he expected on Saturday in Mexico a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, in order to respectfully treat the maritime conflict following a ruling of the ICC challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these paths - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he underlined.
"I hope to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible," Santos said.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Defence Ministers of the Block also met in the run-up to the adoption of the 2013 action plan to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru holds the presidency of the regional bloc.
