Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed HIV-positive.
“It was like a bomb hit,” he says about the moment he received the diagnosis, which the doctor tried to “weaken” without recognizable success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it; and this with such dedication that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he came after several battles in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmas.
At the time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who do not know about their disease and who have already been harmed by the virus and have exhausted their immune system, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who receives treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," explained the head of the HCG's HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, stating that this information was supported by a respected scientific publication in April this year.
Infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and the quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at initiation of treatment, and that those who do not have a drug addiction have a greater chance of having 50 years of CD4 and up to 30 years of CD.
Simply put, the above statements mean that anyone who is diagnosed with HIV positive at the age of 25, in this sense, "can easily live to be 75 years old as long as he is under control," explained this expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
Even though mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA annual report), it is true that 60 percent of the patients recorded in the national database have died since the emergence of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and by the month of May this year there have already been 187 deaths; however, it is assured that universal access to the antiretroviral drugs has been available since 2005.
So why are people still dying from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least over the past 12 years, we have not had any supply problems with the drugs. The problem is that the people come in a far advanced state because they do not know their condition of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to influence global mortality, premature diagnosis is required, which is why massive recognition tests must be offered to all individuals who are required to do so."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (state committee on AIDS prevention in Jalisco) and patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private lab, agreed with this proposal, and this for the only reason that it had been a friend of him who had made a complication that was even the kind of cancer in spite of his young age.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don’t want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was for improvement, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," Fabrizio notes, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are scared today as part of the global AIDS Day.
The sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like everyone else.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara who has taken on the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the places designated for this purpose, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; they used to be handed over individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who don't have access to a condom," he said.
Those at risk for new infections include young people.
"Why do you need them?" is a common mockery of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health care system who do not want to expose themselves, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in dispensers in public toilets of facilities that are often visited by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They should not be paid the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether conservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality doesn't look like that; the best thing to do is to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity," he said.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th in both new and accumulated AIDS cases, and 13th in terms of HIV.
92% of infections occur via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because for every registered case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know it.
After the United States Court of Appeal has confirmed a ruling that does not recognize the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s liabilities achieved through a trade bankruptcy in Mexico, a sinister precedent is set for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has payment problems.
So one could say that the procedures for the survival of companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the land of stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the June 15 recognition of the verdict by Judge Harlin Hale at the Bancarrotas Northern District Court in Texas has led Mexican companies to be vulnerable to seizure of their property across the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the Supreme Court of the United States for three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that creditors must be subject to United States bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, headquartered in New Orleans, first says that the main case is the trade bankruptcy dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of companies with a cross-border profile is unknown.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created, using the American Law Institute as a conciliator.
Secondly, the judgment stipulates that without the company’s votes after recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy mass held by Vitro’s branches with its parent company, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case in which this scheme was approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities among companies of the group have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute for Commercial Bankruptcies).
It is also correct that, after the branch’s votes had been deducted, Vitro’s creditors, the creditors who sued Vitro in the United States courts, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation from 2008 onwards as part of the major economic crisis in the United States that struck the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family appeals to the same Court of Appeal so that the vote is taken in plenary, i.e. by all judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not granted, the Cerciorare appeal will be filed, demanding the review of the case by a higher authority, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The serious thing about this case is that the court set aside a document sent by the government of Mexico under the figura amicus curiae (friend of the court), describing the procedure carried out by Vitro under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, and pointing out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the Bankruptcy Act of the United States.
It is also pointed out that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee the equality of debtors and creditors.
Two-band carambole: a blow for Vitro and for the country.
