Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball’s globetrotter, Héctor “Hetin” Reyes, has been associated with basketball for more than 60 years and has traveled the whole world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large spiritual collection of the country's history of basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to a wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a lower-class player, first-national league player, plenipotentiary and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"All my life I put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 90s," Reyes recalled during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most because I was part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as a managing director, co-manager or coach.
It was many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy’s debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good manager," Reyes says.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), saying to me, "I have a very strong and 2m tall player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would provide for another.
The Vaqueros with Gausse championship was granted to him, but from a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his enforcements and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we first won the pre-Olympic Tournament in Mexico against the US.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, which should have been bronze, if not for this Canadian referee who made us repeat the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as the one who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
My favorite, however, is the 1991 Pan American Games team in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the US team a fight, as they did when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
The team included not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 because of a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great pleasure, was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic Tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourrutiner as a substitute for the suspended players due to the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against any forecast.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was certainly Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculín.
And this without considering his career in the various leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
That is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I really like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best thing you have achieved in the association?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN up to 17 teams in a season at the beginning of the 90s.
What's left to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalization of the lower categories.
That the guys in Ponce, for example, only play in their territory and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today, children make unnecessarily many trips and games.
At least I see the result of the prescribed training and courses for coaches, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch videos of music of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and sometimes I go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always by my side.
Larry Hagman is dead.
Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played a ruthless, insidious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 80s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. on a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications, according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked the most," the family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas" Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in 1965 to 1970 with the sitcom "Enchanting Jeannie" of the television station NBC.
There he played astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is turned upside down when he meets an attractive "Ginn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He also acted in two short-lived comedies, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His cinematic works included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchantingly detestable J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the television chain CBS about the Ewing clan and other figures in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Shot J.R.?", which was supposed to create an expectation for an episode full of emotions where Hagmann's character was nearly killed, led to international speculation, and millions of dollars were wagered in betting houses.
The series set a viewer record at that time.
When the answer became known in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million viewers who turned "Dallas" into the second most viewed entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was Kristin, the sister-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who had shot.
